The aim of this study was to investigate the impact of temperature on the rate of atrial fibrillation (AF) and atrial flutter (AFL). We analyzed the data of 100 patients with AF and AFL who were admitted to our hospital between January 2018 and December 2019. The patients were divided into two groups based on the temperature at the time of admission: a low-temperature group (≤20°C) and a high-temperature group (>20°C). We compared the rate of AF and AFL between the two groups. The results showed that the rate of AF and AFL was significantly higher in the low-temperature group compared to the high-temperature group (P < 0.05). The impact of temperature on the incidence of atrial fibrillation     
Atrial fibrillation (AF) is a common cardiac arrhythmia that can be triggered by various factors, including changes in temperature. This study aimed to investigate the relationship between temperature and the incidence of AF. We analyzed data from a large cohort of patients with AF and found that the incidence of AF was significantly higher during periods of low temperature. Our findings suggest that cold temperatures may trigger AF in susceptible individuals, potentially through mechanisms related to changes in cardiac electrophysiology.
